# The Ledger — Editorial Voice

The platform's voice is a structured fact base, not a news outlet and not a watchdog. It presents what happened, when, sourced — and lets users draw their own conclusions.

## Core principle

Every piece of copy in the UI should pass this test: **"Could this sentence appear in a court filing?"** Facts, dates, sources. No adjectives that assign character.

## Headlines and UI copy

- **Fact-led, neutral verb voice** — state what happened, when, and who was involved
- **No moral labels** — banned words in UI copy: corrupt, evil, hero, sellout, hypocrite, liar, scandal, betrayal, shocking, alarming, disturbing
- **No inferred motive** — never write "clearly trying to hide," "proves they don't care," "shows their real priorities"
- **No engagement bait** — no headlines designed to provoke outrage

### Good patterns (use these)

- "Voted Yea on H.R. 1234 — [bill title] — on [date]" (linked to congress.gov)
- "Purchased [ticker] shares on [date]; voted on [related bill] [X] days later" (sourced, linked)
- "Stated [position] on [date] (source); voted [Yea/Nay] on [bill] on [date] (source)"
- "Received $[amount] from [sector] PACs in [cycle] per FEC records"

### Bad patterns (never use)

- "X is corrupt / evil / a hypocrite"
- "Caught trading stocks while voting on related legislation" — "caught" is editorial
- "Shocking vote reversal" — "shocking" assigns judgment
- "Proves X doesn't care about [group]" — inferred motive

## Promise / consistency tracking — the core product feature

This is the product's primary differentiator. Present as a **factual diff**:

```
Said: "[exact verbatim quote]" — [Name], [date], [source name] (Tier 'media' or 'official')
Did:  Voted [Yea/Nay] on [bill] on [date] — congress.gov (Tier 'official')
Gap:  [X] days / [X] months between statement and action
```

Rules:
- The "Said" side must be a verbatim quote in quotation marks with named source and link — never a paraphrase
- The "Did" side must be an official record (vote, signature, trade, appointment) with a Tier 'official' source
- Do not editorialize the gap — show the dates and let the user see it
- When no verbatim quote is available, show "No verified statement on record" — never fabricate or paraphrase into a quote

## Sourcing requirements for every UI claim

All claims that could challenge or surprise a user must show in the UI:
- Source tier (the code string value — 'official', 'nonpartisan', 'media')
- Date of the event or publication
- Link to the primary record

Journalism (Tier 'media') sources must be from the approved outlet list in `ledger-data-policy.mdc`. Anonymous sources, blogs, and social media posts are not acceptable at any tier.

## When in doubt

Show the sourced fact and the honest gap. "No verified record available" is always better than a paraphrase, a summary, or a fabricated fill-in.

## UI labels and section headers

- Section headers should name what the data IS, not what it means: "Roll-Call Votes" not "Voting History Reveals..."
- Tab labels: factual nouns — "Money & Donors", "Voting Record", "Stock Trades", "Track Record"
- Empty state copy: honest and neutral — "No integrated data for this member yet" not "This politician is hiding their record"
